<TITLE> US considers Afghan command structure changes </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 WASHINGTON, Mar 4 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - The United States and its allies are considering setting up an American-led command in southern Afghanistan to oversee operations in a key battleground province, US officials said on Wednesday. Putting a two-star Marine general in charge of all military operations in Helmand, including the ongoing campaign in Marjah, could help clear the way for the existing British-led command in southern Afghanistan to focus on the coming battle for Kandahar, the Taliban's birthplace in a neighboring province. "We are looking at new command structures to focus on Helmand. A new command there may be better at setting priorities on the battlefield. It's an option," a US defense official said. Another defense official, who also spoke on condition of anonymity, said any changes would be designed to better manage the thousands of additional American, NATO and Afghan troops who have been deployed to Helmand in recent weeks to clear Taliban fighters from Marjah. US-led forces plan to launch a larger military operation this year to get full control of Kandahar, the biggest test of President Barack Obama's Afghan war strategy. The British commander of NATO forces in southern Afghanistan said last week that NATO forces would sweep toward Kandahar over the next six months. In December, Obama ordered 30,000 additional U.S. troops to Afghanistan to try to secure population centers so the government in Kabul can eventually take ov
